sections.rawText:
Required to be PIC
	◊ Pilot Certificate (61.3)
	◊ Government Issued Photo ID (61.3)
	◊ 18 Years old for commercial license (61.123)
	◊ Medical Certificate (2nd class for commercial privileges) (61.23)
	◊ Flight Review (Or Checkride) within 24 Calendar Months
Be familiar with all info concerning your flight prior to it. -> NWKRAFT (91.103)

Carrying Passengers (61.57)
	◊ 3 Takeoff and Landings
	◊ Same Category and Class and Type if Required
	◊ Within 90 Days
*To fly at night with passengers the landings have to be done between 1 Hour after sunset to 1 hour before sunrise to a full stop.
sections.title: Requirements to Carry Passengers (61.57)

sections.rawText:
Aircraft Documents - ARROW  (91.203)
	• Airworthiness Certificate
	• Registration Certificate - Expires every 7 years or if sold
	• Radio Operating License - For international Use - 10 year duration
	• Operating Limitations - Placards, Markings, POH/AFM
	• Weight and Balance Info - POH/AFM

FAA / Manufacturer Aircraft Notices
Service Bulletins - Manufacturer posts best practice advice but not yet mandatory 

Airworthiness Directives: Issued by FAA, corrects a safety issue and are mandatory to comply with. There are One-Time ADs, Recurring, Emergency, and Time-Limited where you can wait for a certain # of Tach hours or till next annual inspection.

Commercial Regulations
	◊ 119.1e - Exceptions like flight instructor
	◊ 91k - Fractional Ownership , Private Pilot Privileges - like flying somebody to a meeting where flying is the secondary part 
	◊ 121 - Consistently Scheduled routes, Airlines 
	◊ 135 - Unscheduled, Charters
	◊ 125 - Big Planes , applied for operations with maximum payload over 6000 pounds or seating configuration of 20 or more passengers.

Change of Address (61.60)
Must Notify FAA within 30 Days or can no longer use pilot privileges.
Can login and update it instantly online through FAA website.

Transponder Requirements (91.215)
	◊ Class A | B | and C
	◊ Above Class B and C
	◊ Mode C Veil - 30NM around Class B.
	◊ All Airspace at or above 10,000 MSL - unless it's also at or below 2,500 AGL. 
*Since 2020 ADS-B Out is now required everywhere a Transponder is.

Medical Certificates
	◊ Complex Aircraft - Retractable Landing Gear | Flaps | Controllable Propeller
	◊ High Performance - More than 200 Horsepower
	◊ Tailwheel - No Ground Instruction Required.
	◊ Towing - Also need at least 100 hours PIC in Cat and Class and 3 actual or simulated glider tows within last 24 months.

Rule of Three
	◊ Operational Control - Owner or person who can schedule and decide when the plane flies.
	◊ PIC
	◊ Making Money 
Can have two of these three without an air operator certificate as long as its incidental to the business like the owner being flown around himself by a pilot to meetings or something but he can't sell those flights to other people. The flight itself can't be the business, but you can pay somebody to fly the plane.

BasicMed
Maximum Certified Takeoff Weight: 12500 pounds
Maximum 7 total Occupants, 6 total passengers
Maximum Altitude 18000 feet
Maximum Airspeed 250 Knots
Can't operate for compensation or hire except flight instruction
To get it you need to take an online course every 24 Months and a medical exam every 48 months

Gyroscopic Instruments
Power Sources/Principles
	• Rigidity in Space / Vacuum: Attitude Indicator, Heading Indicator
	• Precession / Electricity : Turn Coordinator (also rigidity in space)
Rigidity in Space : A spinning disk (like a gyro) resists changes to and maintains its orientation in space.
Precession : Force applied to a spinning disk is deflected 90 degrees in the direction of rotation.

sections.title: Turn Coordinator
sections.rawText:
Turn Coordinator: Canted Horizontally mounted Gyro that is powered by electricity, the 30 degree canted angle allows it to sense the
Rate of Roll while still also giving the Rate of Turn like a Turn and Slip Indicator.

sections.title: Attitude Indicator
sections.rawText:
Attitude Indicator: Horizontally mounted Gyro that spins from a Vacuum Pump and maintains the Horizons attitude using rigidity in space, 
and then the instrument housing moves around it showing pitch and bank changes with the reference arms. 
Avoids precession errors by having pendulous vanes on the bottom that are held down by gravity which cover air holes 
that create a force on one side if the moved off its position that will move it back to align the vanes with the air holes again.

sections.title: Heading Indicator
sections.rawText:
Heading Indicator: Vertically mounted Gyro that spins from a Vacuum Pump and maintains the aircraft heading orientation, 
has to be adjusted to the current heading based on the magnetic compass initially and then every 15 mins
 to account for precession throwing it off.

Attitude Heading Reference System (AHRS)
Replaces the Gyroscopic System with micro-electronic Gyros that use vibrations, accelerometers that use gravitational force, and a magnetometer or flux valve that measures the Earth's magnetic field strength and direction. Rate and tilt sensors.

sections.title: Power On Stall
sections.rawText:
Simulates Takeoff / Go-Around Configuration
Power 1500 RPM 
Hold altitude until 60 - 65 kts - some do 55 but then stall happens almost instantly
Then go Full Power and Pitch for 25 degrees
Hold until Stall occurs - Call Out Stall Horn
Recover

sections.title: Power Off Stall
sections.rawText:
Power Off Stall - Simulates Landing Configuration Stall
Power 1800 RPM
Below 110 Kts - Flaps 10
Below 85 Kts - Flaps 20
Flaps 30
Pitch for 65 kts with a stabilized descent
Then power idle and pitch up to around 5 degrees 
Hold until Stall occurs - Call Out Stall Horn
Recover

sections.title: Chandelles
sections.rawText:
What: A max performance climb with 180 turn

Clean configuration
1500 ft AGL
105 knots - around 2300 RPM
Bug heading - you get +- 10 degrees 
First 90 Degrees
Max power - stay level 
30 degrees bank quickly
Then Slowly increase pitch to 15 degrees right at 90 degrees
Second 90 Degrees
Hold nose at 15 degrees - Requires more back pressure 
Slowly bring bank to 0 right at 180 degrees
*Airspeed should end around 60 knots - stall speed is 48 clean - stall horn happens around 10 knots above that

sections.title: Steep Turns
sections.rawText:
Steep Turns
Altitude: +/- 100 ft
Entry Speed: 95 Knots +/- 10 Knots
Bank Angle: 50 ° +/- 5°
At 30 ° start to increase back pressure and add power

sections.title: Steep Spiral
sections.rawText:
What: 3x360 turns while descending and maintaining your distance around a point with wind correction  

Clean configuration 
80 knots 
Finish no lower than 1500ft AGL
Each 360 you should give yourself 1000 ft 
So start at or above 4500 ft AGL
Have to use less than 60 degree bank
Airspeed and heading you get +- 10
Start
Find a point on the ground and put it under the wheel on your side 
Start into a headwind - so the least steep bank to start - bug heading 
Downwind you make it more steep 
Tail wind is the most steep 
Upwind is mid steep like downwind 
Start power idle 
Let nose come down and start turn 
Use trim for airspeed
When you finish one 360 smoothly add power to at least green to clear the engine 
Should be a few around 3 seconds to put it in and then a few to take it out

sections.title: Accelerated Stall
sections.rawText:
◊ Never go to full break 
Why: Show the danger of adding too much bank on base to final and stall spins 

Clean configuration
85 knots 
No lower than 3000 ft AGL
No airspeed or heading requirements
Start
Power idle 
Bank 45 degrees
Nose up/Hold Altitude to induce stall
At first indication - Acknowledge it
Go wings level and max power
Right rudder on recovery to the right  
Climb out Vx or Vy
Level to Cruise

sections.title: Lazy Eights
sections.rawText:
Clean configuration 
Airspeed 105 knots 
Bug heading
At or above 1500 AGL
Start
Bank and pitch Slowly to 15 for the first 45 degrees 
Bank to 30 and pitch to 0 to 90 degrees 
Bank 15 pitch around -10 to 135 degrees 
Bank and pitch to 0 at 180 
Then to the other side same thing
At each point need to be +- 10 knots +- 100 ft and +- 10 degrees heading 
Should hit the degrees and pitch slowly right as you hit the degrees should never really be holding an attitude 
Tips 
Around 90 degrees marks make sure you are on top of rudder

sections.title: Eights on Pylons
sections.rawText:
Pivotal altitude: Ground speed squared divided by 11.3 + elevation 
Clean configuration 
Doesn’t have the altitude restriction of 1500 AGL
Start at 2500 MSL
95 knots 

Find two points 
Get to pivotal altitude 
Position for 45 degrees quartering tailwind 
Bug heading. - entry heading is also exit heading 
Fly until first point is abeam your shoulder
This has to be done with a crosswind from the points  
When ground speed goes down pitch goes down and vice versa
You fly about 5 seconds when you level out 
If the point starts to get in front of your wing you push forward and if it moves back you pull back

sections.title: Power Off 180
sections.rawText:
Pattern is the same until abeam the touchdown point then
Power idle 
Continue downwind and turn base half the normal distance 
When you level make sure you aren’t low 
You want to start final high

If you have less than 10 total knots of wind in any direction go flaps 10 at power idle 
If more than 10 knots don’t go flaps 10
Aim for 70 knots don’t force it though let it happen and hold it
